Error reading large tif

Ben Weinstein

July 4, 2015

Hi all,

I recieved a orthomosiac image from a colloborator that im reading into R. The file was captured using a unmanned aerial vehicle and stiched in Agisoft Photoscan, and the resulting .tif was sent to me.

The file is quite large (~4gb on disk) and at high resolution.

When i read in using raster, everything seems fine. The extent matches the correct location on the earths surface.

library(raster)
## Loading required package: sp
library(rgdal)

r<-raster(fil<-paste(droppath,"Droning/AgisoftFull20150425_Run3.tif",sep="/"))

However if i try to perform any operation on the image, i recieve an error.

r2<-crop(r,extent(r)/2)
## Error: Failure during raster IO

Ive tried over mulitple computers, reading as brick/stack/raster, reinstalling rgdal/raster, reinstalling R and playing around with the file names. There was a second file that was made using the same software that is much smaller (~300mb) that reads in fine.

d<-raster(fil<-paste(droppath,"Droning/AgisoftFull20150425_Run3_DEM.tif",sep="/"))

Given the huge file size, i assume that this is has to do with memory (as been suggested elsewhere) - although checking out the task manager, i see no memory spike and it appears to be a formatting error for gdal. Ive tried reading direct with gdal, and that fails, even when reading just a portion.

rg<-readGDAL(fil,band=1)
## C:/Users/Ben/Dropbox//Droning/AgisoftFull20150425_Run3_DEM.tif has GDAL driver GTiff 
## and has 9972 rows and 8783 columns
rg<-readGDAL(fil,band=1,output.dim = c(1000,1000))
## C:/Users/Ben/Dropbox//Droning/AgisoftFull20150425_Run3_DEM.tif has GDAL driver GTiff 
## and has 9972 rows and 8783 columns

I appreciate all suggestions on what might be malformed that would prevent gdal from reading the file, but raster to extract the correct metadata. Whats even stranger is that my collaborator claims she was able to open this file in R using the exact same procedure as above. We are both on windows.

I apologize for the lack of reproducibility, im looking for opinions on next steps in debugging.
